  "transcript": "DR: Morning, Dolores — good to see you. You're here to plan the follow-up colonoscopy, and it looks like a few things have come up. How have you been?\nPT: Mostly okay, but honestly a little worried. The main thing is I've had some bleeding — when I go to the bathroom, there's been blood a few times over the last three weeks or so. Not every time, but enough that I noticed.\nDR: I'm glad you're telling me. Bright red, or darker?\nPT: Bright red, on the paper mostly. And I've been more tired than usual.\nDR: Okay. That's exactly the kind of thing we want to sort out with the scope. Let me go through your list. The chart has you on iron — the ferrous sulfate — for the low blood count. Are you still taking that?\nPT: No, I stopped that a while back. Maybe four months ago? It really backed me up, the constipation was rough, so I quit it and never restarted.\nDR: Got it — so no iron for about four months. That matters, because your last labs still show the anemia, hemoglobin around ten. We'll need to address that. And the pantoprazole for the reflux — still on that?\nPT: Yes, that one I take every morning, it works well.\nDR: Good. Any allergies I should have down? I don't see any listed.\nPT: Just — amoxicillin. I got hives from it once, years ago. I always tell people but I'm not sure it's written anywhere.\nDR: Thank you, I'll get that added. So: bleeding, ongoing anemia off iron, and we're due for the surveillance scope anyway from the 2023 polyp. Let's get you scheduled and I'll set up the prep.\nPT: That makes sense. Do I need to stop anything before?\nDR: We'll go over the prep instructions and what to hold. I'll have the team reach out.",
  "note": "**Subjective:** Ms. Vane is a 54-year-old woman presenting to GI clinic to plan surveillance colonoscopy (tubular adenoma with low-grade dysplasia on 2023 colonoscopy, due 2026). She reports new intermittent hematochezia over the past ~3 weeks — bright red blood per rectum, not with every bowel movement — accompanied by increased fatigue. She reports she discontinued ferrous sulfate approximately 4 months ago due to constipation and has not restarted it. Reflux remains well controlled on pantoprazole 40 mg daily. She reports a prior hives reaction to amoxicillin, not previously documented.\n\n**Objective:** Recent labs (2026-06-12): hemoglobin 10.2 g/dL, ferritin 8 ug/L, hematocrit 31.4% — consistent with ongoing iron-deficiency anemia. \n\n**Assessment & Plan:**\n- New hematochezia with iron-deficiency anemia, off iron x4 months — will expedite surveillance/diagnostic colonoscopy.\n- Iron-deficiency anemia — restart oral iron with alternate-day dosing to improve tolerability; discuss if bleeding source found.\n- Update medication list: ferrous sulfate discontinued per patient.\n- Add allergy: amoxicillin (hives).\n- GERD — continue pantoprazole 40 mg daily.\n- Colonoscopy scheduling + bowel prep instructions to follow; return precautions for heavy bleeding.",
  "after_visit_summary": "Visit summary\n\nWhat we discussed\n• New rectal bleeding and tiredness\n• Ongoing low blood count (anemia)\n• Follow-up colonoscopy (due this year)\n• Reflux\n\nNext steps\n• We will schedule your colonoscopy; the team will send prep instructions and what to stop before.\n• Restart iron, taking it every other day to be gentler on your stomach.\n• We updated your record: iron marked stopped; amoxicillin allergy (hives) added.\n• Keep taking pantoprazole each morning.\n• Call for heavy bleeding, lightheadedness, or worsening tiredness.",
  "after_visit_summary_provenance": {
    "method": "deterministic_extractive_v1",
    "source": "clinical_note_assessment_and_plan",
    "review_status": "not_clinically_reviewed"
  }
}